{"id":"astro-ph/9909512","submitter":"Sylvie Vauclair","authors":"Sylvie Vauclair","title":"On the possible existence of a self-regulating hydrodynamical process in\n  slowly rotating stars : I Setting the stage","comments":"9 pages, 7 figures, to be published in A&A","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  It has been known for a long time (Mestel 1953) that the meridional\ncirculation velocity in stars, in the presence of mu-gradients, is the sum of\ntwo terms, one due to the classical thermal imbalance (omega-currents) and the\nother one due to the induced horizontal mu-gradients (mu-induced currents, of\nmu-currents in short). In the most general cases, mu-currents are opposite to\nomega-currents. Simple expressions for these currents are derived under some\nsimplifying physical assumptions presented in the text, and their physical\ninterpretations are discussed. Computations of the omega and mu-currents in a\n0.8 Mo halo stellar model including classical element settling show that the\nmu-currents are larger (in absolute values) than the omega-currents in all the\nstar : some new physics has thus to be invoked in this case. We show here how\nsuch processes could possibly lead to a quasi-equilibrium stage in which both\nthe circulation and the helium settling could be cancelled out. As lithium\ndiffuses in the same way as helium, we expect a very small lithium\nconcentration gradient below the convective zone in \"plateau stars\" (main\nsequence PopII stars), much smaller than the one expected for pure element\nsettling. This could possibly account for the very small dispersion observed\nfor the lithium abundances at the surface of these stars. This should also have\nimportant consequences in other contexts which will be discussed in forthcoming\npapers. The present computations show that element settling in slowly rotating\nstars leads to surface abundances which depend on the competition between\nmu-currents and omega-currents, in a way which had not been taken into account\nin previous computations. This may change our general understanding of the\ndiffusion processes of chemical species in rotating stars.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 30 Sep 1999 16:35:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
