{"id":"nucl-th/9910001","submitter":"Desplanques","authors":"A. Amghar, B. Desplanques","title":"Relationship of field-theory based single boson exchange potentials to\n  current ones","comments":"LaTeX, 37 pages, 14 figures, submitted for publication","journal-ref":"Few Body Syst. 28 (2000) 65-101","doi":"10.1007/s006010070025","report-no":"INS99-24","categories":"nucl-th","license":null,"abstract":"  It is shown that field-theory based single boson exchange potentials cannot\nbe identified to those of the Yukawa or Coulomb type that are currently\ninserted in the Schr\\\"odinger equation. The potential which is obtained rather\ncorresponds to this current single boson exchange potential corrected for the\nprobability that the system under consideration is in a two-body component,\ntherefore missing contributions due to the interaction of these two bodies\nwhile bosons are exchanged. The role of these contributions, which involve at\nleast two boson exchanges, is examined. The conditions that allow one to\nrecover the usual single boson exchange potential are given. It is shown that\nthe present results have some relation: i) to the failure of the Bethe-Salpeter\nequation in reproducing the Dirac or Klein-Gordon equations in the limit where\none of the constituent has a large mass, ii) to the absence of corrections of\nrelative order alpha log(1/alpha) to a full calculation of the binding energy\nin the case of neutral massless bosons or iii) to large corrections of\nwave-functions calculated perturbatively in some light-front approaches.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 1 Oct 1999 05:53:27 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-10-31"}
{"id":"nucl-th/9910002","submitter":"Andres P. Zuker","authors":"A. P. Zuker","title":"Binomial level densities","comments":"4 pages 2 figures Second version (previous not totally superseeded)","journal-ref":"Phys.Rev. C64 (2001) 021303","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevC.64.021303","report-no":null,"categories":"nucl-th","license":null,"abstract":"  It is shown that nuclear level densities in a finite space are described by a\ncontinuous binomial function, determined by the first three moments of the\nHamiltonian, and the dimensionality of the underlying vector space.\nExperimental values for $^{55}$Mn, $^{56}$Fe, and $^{60}$Ni are very well\nreproduced by the binomial form, which turns out to be almost perfectly\napproximated by Bethe's formula with backshift. A proof is given that binomial\ndensities reproduce the low moments of Hamiltonians of any rank: A strong form\nof the famous central limit result of Mon and French. Conditions under which\nthe proof may be extended to the full spectrum are examined.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 1 Oct 1999 14:13:43 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 26 May 2001 18:51:08 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-10-31"}
